(Description)
Implement a first in first out (FIFO) queue using only two stacks. 
The implemented queue should support all the functions of a normal queue (push, peek, pop, and empty).

--- Solution ---
class MyQueue {
    private Stack<Integer> origin;
    private Stack<Integer> cleaner;

    public MyQueue() {
        origin = new Stack<>();
        cleaner = new Stack<>();
    }
    
    public void push(int x) {
        origin.push(x);
    }
    
    public int pop() {
        while(origin.size() > 1) {
            cleaner.push(origin.pop());
        }
        int first = origin.pop();
        while(cleaner.size() >= 1) {
            origin.push(cleaner.pop());
        }
        return first;
    }
    
    public int peek() {
        while(origin.size() > 1) {
            cleaner.push(origin.pop());
        }
        int first = origin.peek();
        while(cleaner.size() >= 1) {
            origin.push(cleaner.pop());
        }
        return first;
    }
    
    public boolean empty() {
        return origin.isEmpty();
    }
}

--- Approach ---
Major difference between two data sets, Queue and Stack, is
- Queue: FIFO : (First In First Out)
- Stack: LIFO : (Last In First Out)

Because Queue should be implemented by two stacks, two stacks were generated for different purposes.
- First Stack: Pushing every values into this stack, so that it maintain same order with Queue.
- Second Stack: When stack should do pop() or peek() like Queue, first Stack should move out every values into second Stack until only one is left, that is what Queue wants.
                Then, it moves back all of the values after figuring out the value which should be returned as a Queue.
